{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_41","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"ps -eo pid,etime,stat,cmd | rg '[p]ytest -q' || true; wc -c /tmp/agent_orchestrator_full2.log\"","aggregated_output":" 735257       12:07 S    python3 .orchestrator/lib/runtime_wrapper.py run --experiment-id obs-followups-2026-07-18 --task-id obs-persist --attempt 1 --runtime codex --model auto --workdir /workspaces/agent-orchestrator/.orchestrator/worktrees/obs-persist-a1 --branch task/obs-persist/a1 --command-json [\"codex\", \"exec\", \"--sandbox\", \"workspace-write\", \"--cd\", \"/workspaces/agent-orchestrator/.orchestrator/worktrees/obs-persist-a1\", \"--skip-git-repo-check\", \"--json\", \"-o\", \"/tmp/claude-0/-workspaces-agent-orchestrator/1c1c961b-6d61-41d6-848a-da60812c189f/scratchpad/task-obs-persist-lastmsg.txt\", \"# Task: persist process-lifecycle observations, not just log them\\n\\nRepo: agent-orchestrator, backend/ (Python, hexagonal architecture \\u2014 read CLAUDE.md at repo\\nroot first).\\n\\n## The gap (found in code review of a prior task)\\n\\n`backend/src/infra/runtime/process_supervisor.py`'s `supervise_process()` already builds\\ncorrect `TelemetryObservation` objects (via `app/observations.py`) for `PROCESS_STARTED` and\\n`PROCESS_EXITED`/`PROCESS_TIMED_OUT`, and passes them to an `on_observation` callback. But the\\ncaller \\u2014 `CliAgentRunner._run_sync` in `backend/src/infra/runtime/cli_runner.py` \\u2014 only forwards\\nthem to `structlog` (`log.info(\\\"runtime.process_observation\\\", ...)`). Nothing persists them to\\nthe durable observation ledger, so they never reach `GET /api/metrics` or any other read model \\u2014\\nthey're diagnostic-log-only, not canonical evidence.\\n\\n## The existing pattern to copy\\n\\n`backend/src/infra/reasoner/openai_reasoner.py` already does this correctly for reasoner usage:\\nread it (constructor around line 270-300, the append call around line 330-340). It takes an\\noptional `observation_repository: ObservationRepository | None = None` constructor parameter and\\ncalls `await self._observation_repository.append(observation)`. The composition root wires it in\\n`backend/src/infra/container.py`'s `reasoner` cached property, passing `self.observation_repository`\\ninto `build_reasoner(...)`.\\n\\n`build_agent_runner(...)` (same container.py, `agent_runner` cached property) does **not**\\ncurrently receive `observation_repository` \\u2014 only `orchestrator_home`. Extend it the same way\\n`orchestrator_home` was threaded through in a prior task: `container.py` \\u2192 `build_agent_runner`\\n(`factory.py`) \\u2192 `CatalogAgentRunner.__init__` \\u2192 `CatalogAgentRunner._runner_for` \\u2192 each\\n`CliAgentRunner` subclass constructor (`PiAgentRunner`/`ClaudeCodeRunner`/`GeminiRunner`), same\\ndefault-`None` optional-parameter style already used for `orchestrator_home`.\\n\\n## The sync/async boundary \\u2014 read this carefully\\n\\n`_run_sync` runs inside `asyncio.to_thread(self._run_sync, ...)` (see `CliAgentRunner.run()`) \\u2014\\nit is a **synchronous** function running in a worker thread. `supervise_process`'s\\n`on_observation` callback is invoked synchronously from within that same call (never from the\\nreader threads \\u2014 only the main supervisor flow calls it, at process start and at\\nexit/timeout, so there's no concurrent-write hazard). You **cannot** `await` an async\\nrepository method from inside that synchronous callback.\\n\\nThe correct fix: have `_run_sync` collect the `TelemetryObservation` objects it receives into a\\nplain list (a local list created by the caller and mutated in place, or however you find\\ncleanest \\u2014 it must survive both the success path and the `TaskFailed`-raising paths, since a\\ntimeout or non-zero exit still produces a `PROCESS_TIMED_OUT`/`PROCESS_EXITED` observation worth\\nkeeping). Back in the **async** `run()` method, after `await asyncio.to_thread(self._run_sync,\\n...)` completes (or raises `TaskFailed` \\u2014 persist what was collected before re-raising), iterate\\nthe collected observations and `await self._observation_repository.append(observation)` for\\neach, exactly like the reasoner does.\\n\\nPersistence must be **best-effort and isolated from task success/failure** \\u2014 matches the\\nexisting `event_sink` pattern in this same file (e.g. how `AgentEvent` emission never blocks or\\nfails the task). If `self._observation_repository` is `None` (not configured, e.g. dry-run or a\\ntest double), skip persistence entirely \\u2014 don't error. Wrap the persist loop so an exception\\nwhile appending observations is logged (structlog) and swallowed, never propagated to fail an\\notherwise-successful task.\\n\\n## Constraints\\n\\n- Do NOT touch `backend/src/domain/`.\\n- Do NOT change the `AgentRunner` port's `run()` method signature \\u2014 this is a constructor-level\\n  dependency, not a per-call parameter (same reasoning as `orchestrator_home`).\\n- Keep the existing `log.info(\\\"runtime.process_observation\\\", ...)` structlog call too \\u2014 it's\\n  still useful for live debugging; this task is additive (persist AND log), not replace-one-with-\\n  the-other.\\n- `mypy src` must stay clean. Follow existing code style.\\n\\n## Verification (run yourself; report exact output)\\n\\n```\\ncd backend\\nruff check src tests --fix\\nmypy src\\npytest -m \\\"not integration\\\" -k \\\"cli_runner or process_supervisor or observation or reasoner or factory\\\"\\npytest -q\\n```\\n\\nWrite at least one focused test proving observations actually reach the repository (a fake/in-\\nmemory `ObservationRepository` \\u2014 check `src/app/testing/` for an existing fake to reuse before\\nwriting a new one) for both the success path and a failure/timeout path. All commands must pass\\nbefore you finish; the full suite (currently 453 passing, 5 skipped) must show zero regressions.\\n\\n## When done\\n\\nSummarize files changed and paste the verification output. Don't claim success without having\\nactually run the commands above in this worktree.\\n\"] --timeout-seconds 1500\n 735258       12:07 Sl   codex exec --sandbox workspace-write --cd /workspaces/agent-orchestrator/.orchestrator/worktrees/obs-persist-a1 --skip-git-repo-check --json -o /tmp/claude-0/-workspaces-agent-orchestrator/1c1c961b-6d61-41d6-848a-da60812c189f/scratchpad/task-obs-persist-lastmsg.txt # Task: persist process-lifecycle observations, not just log them  Repo: agent-orchestrator, backend/ (Python, hexagonal architecture — read CLAUDE.md at repo root first).  ## The gap (found in code review of a prior task)  `backend/src/infra/runtime/process_supervisor.py`'s `supervise_process()` already builds correct `TelemetryObservation` objects (via `app/observations.py`) for `PROCESS_STARTED` and `PROCESS_EXITED`/`PROCESS_TIMED_OUT`, and passes them to an `on_observation` callback. But the caller — `CliAgentRunner._run_sync` in `backend/src/infra/runtime/cli_runner.py` — only forwards them to `structlog` (`log.info(\"runtime.process_observation\", ...)`). Nothing persists them to the durable observation ledger, so they never reach `GET /api/metrics` or any other read model — they're diagnostic-log-only, not canonical evidence.  ## The existing pattern to copy  `backend/src/infra/reasoner/openai_reasoner.py` already does this correctly for reasoner usage: read it (constructor around line 270-300, the append call around line 330-340). It takes an optional `observation_repository: ObservationRepository | None = None` constructor parameter and calls `await self._observation_repository.append(observation)`. The composition root wires it in `backend/src/infra/container.py`'s `reasoner` cached property, passing `self.observation_repository` into `build_reasoner(...)`.  `build_agent_runner(...)` (same container.py, `agent_runner` cached property) does **not** currently receive `observation_repository` — only `orchestrator_home`. Extend it the same way `orchestrator_home` was threaded through in a prior task: `container.py` → `build_agent_runner` (`factory.py`) → `CatalogAgentRunner.__init__` → `CatalogAgentRunner._runner_for` → each `CliAgentRunner` subclass constructor (`PiAgentRunner`/`ClaudeCodeRunner`/`GeminiRunner`), same default-`None` optional-parameter style already used for `orchestrator_home`.  ## The sync/async boundary — read this carefully  `_run_sync` runs inside `asyncio.to_thread(self._run_sync, ...)` (see `CliAgentRunner.run()`) — it is a **synchronous** function running in a worker thread. `supervise_process`'s `on_observation` callback is invoked synchronously from within that same call (never from the reader threads — only the main supervisor flow calls it, at process start and at exit/timeout, so there's no concurrent-write hazard). You **cannot** `await` an async repository method from inside that synchronous callback.  The correct fix: have `_run_sync` collect the `TelemetryObservation` objects it receives into a plain list (a local list created by the caller and mutated in place, or however you find cleanest — it must survive both the success path and the `TaskFailed`-raising paths, since a timeout or non-zero exit still produces a `PROCESS_TIMED_OUT`/`PROCESS_EXITED` observation worth keeping). Back in the **async** `run()` method, after `await asyncio.to_thread(self._run_sync, ...)` completes (or raises `TaskFailed` — persist what was collected before re-raising), iterate the collected observations and `await self._observation_repository.append(observation)` for each, exactly like the reasoner does.  Persistence must be **best-effort and isolated from task success/failure** — matches the existing `event_sink` pattern in this same file (e.g. how `AgentEvent` emission never blocks or fails the task). If `self._observation_repository` is `None` (not configured, e.g. dry-run or a test double), skip persistence entirely — don't error. Wrap the persist loop so an exception while appending observations is logged (structlog) and swallowed, never propagated to fail an otherwise-successful task.  ## Constraints  - Do NOT touch `backend/src/domain/`. - Do NOT change the `AgentRunner` port's `run()` method signature — this is a constructor-level   dependency, not a per-call parameter (same reasoning as `orchestrator_home`). - Keep the existing `log.info(\"runtime.process_observation\", ...)` structlog call too — it's   still useful for live debugging; this task is additive (persist AND log), not replace-one-with-   the-other. - `mypy src` must stay clean. Follow existing code style.  ## Verification (run yourself; report exact output)  ``` cd backend ruff check src tests --fix mypy src pytest -m \"not integration\" -k \"cli_runner or process_supervisor or observation or reasoner or factory\" pytest -q ```  Write at least one focused test proving observations actually reach the repository (a fake/in- memory `ObservationRepository` — check `src/app/testing/` for an existing fake to reuse before writing a new one) for both the success path and a failure/timeout path. All commands must pass before you finish; the full suite (currently 453 passing, 5 skipped) must show zero regressions.  ## When done  Summarize files changed and paste the verification output. Don't claim success without having actually run the commands above in this worktree. \n14328 /tmp/agent_orchestrator_full2.log\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
